[src:stochastic-calculus/feynman-kac-formula] The **Feynman–Kac formula**, named after Richard Feynman and Mark Kac, establishes a link between parabolic partial differential equations and stochastic processes.
[src:stochastic-calculus/feynman-kac-formula] In 1947, when Kac and Feynman were both faculty members at Cornell University, Kac attended a presentation of Feynman's and remarked that the two of them were working on the same thing from different directions.
[src:stochastic-calculus/feynman-kac-formula] The Feynman–Kac formula resulted, which proves rigorously a real-valued analogy to Feynman's path integrals.
[src:stochastic-calculus/feynman-kac-formula] The complex case, needed in quantum mechanics, is still an open question.
[src:stochastic-calculus/feynman-kac-formula] The formula offers a method of solving certain partial differential equations by simulating random paths of a stochastic process.
[src:stochastic-calculus/feynman-kac-formula] Conversely, it can be used to compute an important class of expectations of random processes by deterministic means.
[src:stochastic-calculus/feynman-kac-formula] where $X_{t}$ is an Itô process satisfying the stochastic differential equation $dX_{t}=\mu (X_{t},t)\,dt+\sigma (X_{t},t)\,dW_{t},$ and $W_{t}$ is the Wiener process (also called Brownian motion).
[src:stochastic-calculus/feynman-kac-formula] Suppose that $X_{t}$ describes the position at time t of a particle that evolves according to the diffusion process $dX_{t}=\mu (X_{t},t)\,dt+\sigma (X_{t},t)\,dW_{t}.$ Let the particle incur "cost" at a rate of $f(X_{s},s)$ at location $X_{s}$ at time s .
[src:stochastic-calculus/feynman-kac-formula] Let it incur a final cost at time T of $\psi (X_{T})$ .
[src:stochastic-calculus/feynman-kac-formula] If the particle is at location $X_{s}$ at time s , then it decays with rate $V(X_{s},s)$ .
[src:stochastic-calculus/feynman-kac-formula] After the particle has decayed away, all future cost is zero.
[src:stochastic-calculus/feynman-kac-formula] A proof that the above expected-value formula is a solution of the differential equation is long, difficult and not presented here.
[src:stochastic-calculus/feynman-kac-formula] It is however reasonably straightforward to show that, *if a solution exists*, it must have the above form.
[src:stochastic-calculus/feynman-kac-formula] with terminal condition $u(x,T)=\psi (x).$ Further let $X_{t}$ be a stochastic process as defined above.
[src:stochastic-calculus/feynman-kac-formula] So we just need to prove $Y_{s}$ is a martingale.
[src:stochastic-calculus/feynman-kac-formula] When originally published by Kac in 1949, the formula was presented as a means for determining the distribution of certain Wiener functionals.
[src:stochastic-calculus/feynman-kac-formula] Suppose we wish to find the expected value of the function $\exp \left(-\int _{0}^{t}V(x(\tau ))\,d\tau \right)$ in the case where *x*(*t*) is some realization of a diffusion process starting at *x*(0) = 0.
[src:stochastic-calculus/feynman-kac-formula] The Feynman–Kac formula says that this expectation is equivalent to the integral of a solution to a corresponding diffusion equation.
[src:stochastic-calculus/feynman-kac-formula] The Feynman–Kac formula can also be used to evaluate functional integrals of a certain form.
[src:stochastic-calculus/feynman-kac-formula] In practical applications, the Feynman–Kac formula can be used with numerical methods like Euler-Maruyama to numerically approximate solutions to partial differential equations.
[src:stochastic-calculus/feynman-kac-formula] Consider the convection–diffusion PDE with parameters $b=1$ , $\sigma =1$ and terminal condition $u(x,T)=e^{-x^{2}}$ with $T=1$ .
[src:stochastic-calculus/feynman-kac-formula] where X is an Itô process governed by the SDE $dX_{t}=dt+{\sqrt {2}}dW_{t}$ and $W_{t}$ is a Wiener process.
[src:stochastic-calculus/feynman-kac-formula] Then using the Euler-Maruyama method, the SDE can be numerically integrated forwards in time from the initial condition $(x_{0},t_{0})$ till the terminal time $T,$ yielding simulated values of $X_{T}$ .
[src:stochastic-calculus/feynman-kac-formula] To approximate the expectation in the Feynman-Kac method, the simulation is repeated N times.
[src:stochastic-calculus/feynman-kac-formula] The figure below compares the analytical solution with the numerical approximation obtained using the Euler–Maruyama method with $N=1000$ .
[src:stochastic-calculus/feynman-kac-formula] The left-hand plots show vertical slices of the gradient plot on the right, with each vertical line on the surface corresponding to a colored curve on the left.
[src:stochastic-calculus/feynman-kac-formula] While the numerical solution exhibits some noise, it closely follows the shape of the exact solution.
[src:stochastic-calculus/feynman-kac-formula] Increasing the number of simulations N or decreasing the Euler–Maruyama time step improves the accuracy and reduces the variance of the approximation.
[src:stochastic-calculus/feynman-kac-formula] This example illustrates how stochastic simulation, enabled by the Feynman–Kac formula and numerical methods like Euler–Maruyama, can approximate PDE solutions.
[src:stochastic-calculus/feynman-kac-formula] In practice, such stochastic approaches are especially valuable when dealing with high-dimensional systems or complex geometries where traditional PDE solvers become computationally prohibitive.
[src:stochastic-calculus/feynman-kac-formula] One key advantage of the SDE-based method is its natural parallelism—each simulation, or realization, can be computed independently—making it well-suited for high-performance computing environments.
[src:stochastic-calculus/feynman-kac-formula] While stochastic simulations introduce variance, this can be mitigated by increasing the number of realizations or refining the time discretization.
[src:stochastic-calculus/feynman-kac-formula] Thus, stochastic differential equations provide a flexible and scalable alternative to deterministic PDE solvers, particularly in contexts where uncertainty is intrinsic or dimensionality poses a computational barrier.
[src:stochastic-calculus/feynman-kac-formula] In contrast to traditional PDE solvers, which typically require solving for the entire solution over a grid, this method enables direct computation at specific points in space and time.
[src:stochastic-calculus/feynman-kac-formula] This targeted approach allows computational resources to be focused on regions of interest, potentially resulting in substantial efficiency gains.
[src:stochastic-calculus/feynman-kac-formula] In quantitative finance, the Feynman–Kac formula is used to efficiently calculate solutions to the Black–Scholes equation to price options on stocks and zero-coupon bond prices in affine term structure models.
[src:stochastic-calculus/feynman-kac-formula] For example, consider a stock price $S_{t}$ undergoing geometric Brownian motion $dS_{t}=\left(r_{t}dt+\sigma _{t}dW_{t}\right)S_{t}$ where $r_{t}$ is the risk-free interest rate and $\sigma _{t}$ is the volatility.
[src:stochastic-calculus/feynman-kac-formula] Equivalently, by Itô's lemma, $d\ln S_{t}=\left(r_{t}-{\tfrac {1}{2}}\sigma _{t}^{2}\right)dt+\sigma _{t}\,dW_{t}.$ Now consider a European call option on an $S_{t}$ expiring at time T with strike K .
[src:stochastic-calculus/feynman-kac-formula] The same calculation shows that its price $u(x,t)$ satisfies ${\begin{cases}\partial _{t}u+Au-r_{t}u=0\\u(x,T)=g(x).\end{cases}}$ Some other options like the American option do not have a fixed expiry.
[src:stochastic-calculus/feynman-kac-formula] Some options have value at expiry determined by the past stock prices.
[src:stochastic-calculus/feynman-kac-formula] For example, an **average option** has a payoff that is not determined by the underlying price at expiry but by the average underlying price over some predetermined period of time.
[src:stochastic-calculus/feynman-kac-formula] For these, the Feynman–Kac formula does not directly apply.
[src:stochastic-calculus/feynman-kac-formula] In quantum chemistry, it is used to solve the Schrödinger equation with the pure diffusion Monte Carlo method.
[src:stochastic-calculus/girsanov-theorem] In probability theory, **Girsanov's theorem** or the **Cameron-Martin-Girsanov theorem** explains how stochastic processes change under changes in measure.
[src:stochastic-calculus/girsanov-theorem] Results of this type were first proved by Cameron-Martin in the 1940s and by Igor Girsanov in 1960.
[src:stochastic-calculus/girsanov-theorem] They have been subsequently extended to more general classes of process culminating in the general form of Lenglart (1977).
[src:stochastic-calculus/girsanov-theorem] Girsanov's theorem is important in the general theory of stochastic processes since it enables the key result that if *Q* is a measure that is absolutely continuous with respect to *P* then every *P*-semimartingale is a *Q*-semimartingale.
[src:stochastic-calculus/girsanov-theorem] We state the theorem first for the special case when the underlying stochastic process is a Wiener process.
[src:stochastic-calculus/girsanov-theorem] This special case is sufficient for risk-neutral pricing in the Black–Scholes model.
[src:stochastic-calculus/girsanov-theorem] Let $\{W_{t}\}$ be a Wiener process on the Wiener probability space $\{\Omega ,{\mathcal {F}},P\}$ .
[src:stochastic-calculus/girsanov-theorem] Let $X_{t}$ be a measurable process adapted to the natural filtration of the Wiener process $\{{\mathcal {F}}_{t}^{W}\}$ ; we assume that the usual conditions have been satisfied.
