[src:stochastic-calculus/local-martingale] However, this PDE itself does not ensure that $M_{t}$ is a martingale.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-calculus] Since the 1970s, the Wiener process has been widely applied in financial mathematics and economics to model the evolution in time of stock prices and bond interest rates.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-calculus] The main flavours of stochastic calculus are the Itô calculus and its variational relative the Malliavin calculus.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-calculus] For technical reasons the Itô integral is the most useful for general classes of processes, but the related Stratonovich integral is frequently useful in problem formulation (particularly in engineering disciplines).
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-calculus] The Stratonovich integral can readily be expressed in terms of the Itô integral, and vice versa.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-calculus] Stochastic integrals do NOT obey the usual chain rule.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-calculus] This enables problems to be expressed in a coordinate system invariant form, which is invaluable when developing stochastic calculus on manifolds other than **R***n*.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-calculus] The dominated convergence theorem does not hold for the Stratonovich integral; consequently it is very difficult to prove results without re-expressing the integrals in Itô form.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-calculus] The Itô integral is central to the study of stochastic calculus.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-calculus] The integral $\int H\,dX$ is defined for a semimartingale *X* and locally bounded **predictable** process *H*.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-calculus] where [*X*, *Y*]*t**c* denotes the optional quadratic covariation of the continuous parts of *X* and *Y*, which is the optional quadratic covariation minus the jumps of the processes X and Y , i.e.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-calculus] is also used to denote the Stratonovich integral.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-calculus] An important application of stochastic calculus is in mathematical finance, in which asset prices are often assumed to follow stochastic differential equations.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-calculus] For example, the Black–Scholes model prices options as if they follow a geometric Brownian motion, illustrating the opportunities and risks from applying stochastic calculus.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-calculus] Besides the classical Itô and Fisk–Stratonovich integrals, many other notions of stochastic integrals exist, such as the Hitsuda–Skorokhod integral, the Marcus integral, and the Ogawa integral.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] A **stochastic differential equation** (**SDE**) is a differential equation in which one or more of the terms is a stochastic process, resulting in a solution which is also a stochastic process.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] SDEs have many applications throughout pure mathematics and are used to model various behaviours of stochastic models such as prices of listed company shares, random growth models or physical systems that are subjected to thermal fluctuations.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] SDEs have a random differential that is in the most basic case random white noise calculated as the distributional derivative of a Brownian motion or more generally a semimartingale.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] However, other types of random behaviour are possible, such as jump processes like Lévy processes or semimartingales with jumps.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] Stochastic differential equations are in general neither differential equations nor random differential equations.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] Random differential equations are conjugate to stochastic differential equations.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] Stochastic differential equations can also be extended to differential manifolds.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] Some of these early examples were linear stochastic differential equations, also called Langevin equations after French physicist Langevin, describing the motion of a harmonic oscillator subject to a random force.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] The mathematical theory of stochastic differential equations was developed in the 1940s through the groundbreaking work of Japanese mathematician Kiyosi Itô, who introduced the concept of stochastic integral and initiated the study of nonlinear stochastic differential equations.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] Another approach was later proposed by Russian physicist Stratonovich, leading to a calculus similar to ordinary calculus.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] The most common form of SDEs in the literature is an ordinary differential equation with the right hand side perturbed by a term dependent on a white noise variable.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] In most cases, SDEs are understood as continuous time limit of the corresponding stochastic difference equations.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] This understanding of SDEs is ambiguous and must be complemented by a proper mathematical definition of the corresponding integral.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] Such a mathematical definition was first proposed by Kiyosi Itô in the 1940s, leading to what is known today as the Itô calculus.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] Another construction was later proposed by Russian physicist Stratonovich, leading to what is known as the Stratonovich integral.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] The Itô integral and Stratonovich integral are related, but different, objects and the choice between them depends on the application considered.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] The Itô calculus is based on the concept of non-anticipativeness or causality, which is natural in applications where the variable is time.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] An alternative view on SDEs is the stochastic flow of diffeomorphisms.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] This understanding is unambiguous and corresponds to the Stratonovich version of the continuous time limit of stochastic difference equations.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] Associated with SDEs is the Smoluchowski equation or the Fokker–Planck equation, an equation describing the time evolution of probability distribution functions.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] The generalization of the Fokker–Planck evolution to temporal evolution of differential forms is provided by the concept of stochastic evolution operator.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] In physical science, there is an ambiguity in the usage of the term "Langevin SDEs".
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] While Langevin SDEs can be of a more general form, this term typically refers to a narrow class of SDEs with gradient flow vector fields.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] This class of SDEs is particularly popular because it is a starting point of the Parisi–Sourlas stochastic quantization procedure, leading to a N=2 supersymmetric model closely related to supersymmetric quantum mechanics.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] From the physical point of view, however, this class of SDEs is not very interesting because it never exhibits spontaneous breakdown of topological supersymmetry, i.e., (overdamped) Langevin SDEs are never chaotic.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] Brownian motion or the Wiener process was discovered to be exceptionally complex mathematically.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] The Wiener process is almost surely nowhere differentiable; thus, it requires its own rules of calculus.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] There are two dominating versions of stochastic calculus, the Itô stochastic calculus and the Stratonovich stochastic calculus.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] Each of the two has advantages and disadvantages, and newcomers are often confused whether the one is more appropriate than the other in a given situation.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] Guidelines exist (e.g. Øksendal, 2003) and conveniently, one can readily convert an Itô SDE to an equivalent Stratonovich SDE and back again.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] Still, one must be careful which calculus to use when the SDE is initially written down.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] Numerical methods for solving stochastic differential equations include the Euler–Maruyama method, Milstein method, Runge–Kutta method (SDE), Rosenbrock method, and methods based on different representations of iterated stochastic integrals.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] In physics, SDEs have wide applicability ranging from molecular dynamics to neurodynamics and to the dynamics of astrophysical objects.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] More specifically, SDEs describe all dynamical systems, in which quantum effects are either unimportant or can be taken into account as perturbations.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] SDEs can be viewed as a generalization of the dynamical systems theory to models with noise.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] This is an important generalization because real systems cannot be completely isolated from their environments and for this reason always experience external stochastic influence.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] There are standard techniques for transforming higher-order equations into several coupled first-order equations by introducing new unknowns.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] If X is a linear space and g are constants, the system is said to be subject to additive noise, otherwise it is said to be subject to multiplicative noise.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] For additive noise, the Itô and Stratonovich forms of the SDE generate the same solution, and it is not important which definition is used to solve the SDE.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] For multiplicative noise SDEs the Itô and Stratonovich forms of the SDE are different, and care should be used in mapping between them.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] For a fixed configuration of noise, SDE has a unique solution differentiable with respect to the initial condition.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] Nontriviality of stochastic case shows up when one tries to average various objects of interest over noise configurations.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] In this sense, an SDE is not a uniquely defined entity when noise is multiplicative and when the SDE is understood as a continuous time limit of a stochastic difference equation.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] In this case, SDE must be complemented by what is known as "interpretations of SDE" such as Itô or a Stratonovich interpretations of SDEs.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] Nevertheless, when SDE is viewed as a continuous-time stochastic flow of diffeomorphisms, it is a uniquely defined mathematical object that corresponds to Stratonovich approach to a continuous time limit of a stochastic difference equation.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] In physics, the main method of solution is to find the probability distribution function as a function of time using the equivalent Fokker–Planck equation (FPE).
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] The Fokker–Planck equation is a deterministic partial differential equation.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] It tells how the probability distribution function evolves in time similarly to how the Schrödinger equation gives the time evolution of the quantum wave function or the diffusion equation gives the time evolution of chemical concentration.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] Alternatively, numerical solutions can be obtained by Monte Carlo simulation.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] The notation used in probability theory (and in many applications of probability theory, for instance in signal processing with the filtering problem and in mathematical finance) is slightly different.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] It is also the notation used in publications on numerical methods for solving stochastic differential equations.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] This notation makes the exotic nature of the random function of time $\xi ^{\alpha }$ in the physics formulation more explicit.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] In strict mathematical terms, $\xi ^{\alpha }$ cannot be chosen as an ordinary function, but only as a generalized function.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] The mathematical formulation treats this complication with less ambiguity than the physics formulation.
