[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] The equation above characterizes the behavior of the continuous time stochastic process *X**t* as the sum of an ordinary Lebesgue integral and an Itô integral.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] This is so because the increments of a Wiener process are independent and normally distributed.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] The function *μ* is referred to as the drift coefficient, while *σ* is called the diffusion coefficient.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] The stochastic process *X**t* is called a diffusion process, and satisfies the Markov property.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] The formal interpretation of an SDE is given in terms of what constitutes a solution to the SDE.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] There are two main definitions of a solution to an SDE, a strong solution and a weak solution Both require the existence of a process *X**t* that solves the integral equation version of the SDE.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] The difference between the two lies in the underlying probability space ( $\Omega ,\,{\mathcal {F}},\,P$ ).
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] A weak solution consists of a probability space and a process that satisfies the integral equation, while a strong solution is a process that satisfies the equation and is defined on a given probability space.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] The Yamada–Watanabe theorem makes a connection between the two.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] which is the equation for the dynamics of the price of a listed company share in the Black–Scholes options pricing model of financial mathematics.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] This leads to models that can deal with the volatility smile in financial mathematics.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] was used by Louis Bachelier as the first model for stock prices in 1900, known today as Bachelier model.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] There are also more general stochastic differential equations where the coefficients *μ* and *σ* depend not only on the present value of the process *X**t*, but also on previous values of the process and possibly on present or previous values of other processes too.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] In that case the solution process, *X*, is not a Markov process, and it is called an Itô process and not a diffusion process.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] When the coefficients depends only on present and past values of *X*, the defining equation is called a stochastic delay differential equation.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] A generalization of stochastic differential equations with the Fisk-Stratonovich integral to semimartingales with jumps are the SDEs of *Marcus type*.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] The Marcus integral is an extension of McShane's stochastic calculus.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] which is the equation for the dynamics of the return of the price of a listed company share under the hypothesis that returns display a Log-normal distribution.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] Under this hypothesis, the methodologies developed by Marcello Minenna determines prediction interval able to identify abnormal return that could hide market abuse phenomena.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] More generally one can extend the theory of stochastic calculus onto differential manifolds and for this purpose one uses the Fisk-Stratonovich integral.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] For each $x\in M$ the map $A(x):E\to T_{x}M$ is linear and $A(\cdot )e\in \Gamma (TM)$ for each $e\in E$ .
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] holds P -almost surely, where $(df)_{X}:T_{x}M\to T_{f(x)}M$ is the differential at X .
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] It follows from the fact that $f(X)$ for each test function $f\in C_{c}^{\infty }(M)$ is a semimartingale, that X is a *semimartingale on M*.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] Although Stratonovich SDEs are the natural choice for SDEs on manifolds, given that they satisfy the chain rule and that their drift and diffusion coefficients behave as vector fields under changes of coordinates, there are cases where Ito calculus on manifolds is preferable.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] A theory of Ito calculus on manifolds was first developed by Laurent Schwartz through the concept of Schwartz morphism, see also the related 2-jet interpretation of Ito SDEs on manifolds based on the jet-bundle.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] This interpretation is helpful when trying to optimally approximate the solution of an SDE given on a large space with the solutions of an SDE given on a submanifold of that space, in that a Stratonovich based projection does not result to be optimal.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] This has been applied to the filtering problem, leading to optimal projection filters.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] Usually the solution of an SDE requires a probabilistic setting, as the integral implicit in the solution is a stochastic integral.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] If it were possible to deal with the differential equation path by path, one would not need to define a stochastic integral and one could develop a theory independently of probability theory.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] as a single deterministic differential equation for every $\omega \in \Omega$ , where $\Omega$ is the sample space in the given probability space ( $\Omega ,\,{\mathcal {F}},\,P$ ).
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] Other definitions of the iterated integral lead to deterministic pathwise equivalents of different stochastic integrals, like the Stratonovich integral.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] This has been used for example in financial mathematics to price options without probability.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] As with deterministic ordinary and partial differential equations, it is important to know whether a given SDE has a solution, and whether or not it is unique.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] The following is a typical existence and uniqueness theorem for Itô SDEs taking values in *n*-dimensional Euclidean space **R***n* and driven by an *m*-dimensional Brownian motion *B*; the proof may be found in Øksendal (2003, §5.2).
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] More generally one can also look at stochastic differential equations on manifolds.
