[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] Let $\zeta :\Omega \to {\overline {\mathbb {R} }}_{+}$ be a predictable stopping time with $\zeta >0$ almost surely.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] $\zeta$ is also a so-called *explosion time*.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] where $Y_{t}=h(X_{t})$ where h is defined as before.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] In supersymmetric theory of SDEs, stochastic dynamics is defined via stochastic evolution operator acting on the differential forms on the phase/state space of the model.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] In this formulation of stochastic dynamics, all SDEs possess topological supersymmetry which represents the preservation of the continuity of the phase space by continuous time flow.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stochastic-differential-equation] The spontaneous breakdown of this supersymmetry is the mathematical essence of the ubiquitous dynamical phenomenon known across disciplines as chaos.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stratonovich-integral] In stochastic processes, the **Stratonovich integral** or **Fisk–Stratonovich integral** (developed simultaneously by Ruslan Stratonovich and Donald Fisk) is a stochastic integral, the most common alternative to the Itô integral.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stratonovich-integral] Although the Itô integral is the usual choice in applied mathematics, the Stratonovich integral is frequently used in physics.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stratonovich-integral] In some circumstances, integrals in the Stratonovich definition are easier to manipulate.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stratonovich-integral] Unlike the Itô calculus, Stratonovich integrals are defined such that the chain rule of ordinary calculus holds.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stratonovich-integral] Perhaps the most common situation in which these are encountered is as the solution to Stratonovich stochastic differential equations (SDEs).
[src:stochastic-calculus/stratonovich-integral] These are equivalent to Itô SDEs and it is possible to convert between the two whenever one definition is more convenient.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stratonovich-integral] The Stratonovich integral can be defined in a manner similar to the Riemann integral, that is as a limit of Riemann sums.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stratonovich-integral] Suppose that $W:[0,T]\times \Omega \to \mathbb {R}$ is a Wiener process and $X:[0,T]\times \Omega \to \mathbb {R}$ is a semimartingale adapted to the natural filtration of the Wiener process.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stratonovich-integral] as the mesh of the partition $0=t_{0}<t_{1}<\dots <t_{k}=T$ of $[0,T]$ tends to 0 (in the style of a Riemann–Stieltjes integral).
[src:stochastic-calculus/stratonovich-integral] The circle $\circ$ is a notational device, used to distinguish this integral from the Itô integral.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stratonovich-integral] This latter rule is akin to the chain rule of ordinary calculus.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stratonovich-integral] Stochastic integrals can rarely be solved in analytic form, making stochastic numerical integration an important topic in all uses of stochastic integrals.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stratonovich-integral] Various numerical approximations converge to the Stratonovich integral, and variations of these are used to solve Stratonovich SDEs (Kloeden & Platen 1992).
[src:stochastic-calculus/stratonovich-integral] Note however that the most widely used Euler scheme (the Euler–Maruyama method) for the numeric solution of Langevin equations requires the equation to be in Itô form.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stratonovich-integral] This notation is often used to formulate stochastic differential equations (SDEs), which are really equations about stochastic integrals.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stratonovich-integral] The Itô integral of the process X with respect to the Wiener process W is denoted by $\int _{0}^{T}X_{t}\,\mathrm {d} W_{t}$ (without the circle).
[src:stochastic-calculus/stratonovich-integral] This integral does not obey the ordinary chain rule as the Stratonovich integral does; instead one has to use the slightly more complicated Itô's lemma.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stratonovich-integral] where f is any continuously differentiable function of two variables W and t and the last integral is an Itô integral (Kloeden & Platen 1992, p.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stratonovich-integral] Langevin equations exemplify the importance of specifying the interpretation (Stratonovich or Itô) in a given problem.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stratonovich-integral] Suppose $X_{t}$ is a time-homogeneous Itô diffusion with continuously differentiable diffusion coefficient $\sigma$ , i.e. it satisfies the SDE $\mathrm {d} X_{t}=\mu (X_{t})\,\mathrm {d} t+\sigma (X_{t})\,\mathrm {d} W_{t}$ .
[src:stochastic-calculus/stratonovich-integral] Obviously, if $\sigma$ is independent of $X_{t}$ , the two interpretations will lead to the same form for the Langevin equation.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stratonovich-integral] In that case, the noise term is called "additive" (since the noise term $dW_{t}$ is multiplied by only a fixed coefficient).
[src:stochastic-calculus/stratonovich-integral] Otherwise, if $\sigma =\sigma (X_{t})$ , the Langevin equation in Itô form may in general differ from that in Stratonovich form, in which case the noise term is called multiplicative (i.e., the noise $dW_{t}$ is multiplied by a function of $X_{t}$ that is $\sigma (X_{t})$ ).
[src:stochastic-calculus/stratonovich-integral] where $[X,Y]_{T}^{c}$ is the continuous part of the covariation.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stratonovich-integral] The Stratonovich integral lacks the important property of the Itô integral, which does not "look into the future".
[src:stochastic-calculus/stratonovich-integral] In many real-world applications, such as modelling stock prices, one only has information about past events, and hence the Itô interpretation is more natural.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stratonovich-integral] In financial mathematics the Itô interpretation is usually used.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stratonovich-integral] In physics, however, stochastic integrals occur as the solutions of Langevin equations.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stratonovich-integral] A Langevin equation is a coarse-grained version of a more microscopic model (Risken 1996); depending on the problem in consideration, Stratonovich or Itô interpretation or even more exotic interpretations such as the isothermal interpretation, are appropriate.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stratonovich-integral] The Stratonovich interpretation is the most frequently used interpretation within the physical sciences.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stratonovich-integral] The Wong–Zakai theorem states that physical systems with non-white noise spectrum characterized by a finite noise correlation time $\tau$ can be approximated by a Langevin equations with white noise in Stratonovich interpretation in the limit where $\tau$ tends to zero.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stratonovich-integral] Because the Stratonovich calculus satisfies the ordinary chain rule, stochastic differential equations (SDEs) in the Stratonovich sense are more straightforward to define on differentiable manifolds, rather than just on $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:stochastic-calculus/stratonovich-integral] The tricky chain rule of the Itô calculus makes it a more awkward choice for manifolds.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stratonovich-integral] In the supersymmetric theory of SDEs, one considers the evolution operator obtained by averaging the pullback induced on the exterior algebra of the phase space by the stochastic flow determined by an SDE.
[src:stochastic-calculus/stratonovich-integral] In this context, it is then natural to use the Stratonovich interpretation of SDEs.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] In mathematics, the **Wiener process** (or **Brownian motion**, due to its historical connection with the physical process of the same name) is a real-valued continuous-time stochastic process named after Norbert Wiener.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] It is one of the best known Lévy processes (càdlàg stochastic processes with stationary independent increments).
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] It occurs frequently in pure and applied mathematics, economics, quantitative finance, evolutionary biology, and physics.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] The Wiener process plays an important role in both pure and applied mathematics.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] In pure mathematics, the Wiener process gave rise to the study of continuous time martingales.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] It is a key process in terms of which more complicated stochastic processes can be described.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] As such, it plays a vital role in stochastic calculus, diffusion processes and even potential theory.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] It is the driving process of Schramm–Loewner evolution.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] In applied mathematics, the Wiener process is used to represent the integral of a white noise Gaussian process, and so is useful as a model of noise in electronics engineering (see Brownian noise), instrument errors in filtering theory and disturbances in control theory.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] The Wiener process has applications throughout the mathematical sciences.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] In physics, researchers use it to model Brownian motion and other types of diffusion, often through the Fokker–Planck and Langevin equations, which describe how random motion evolves over time.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] It also underpins the rigorous path integral formulation of quantum mechanics: by the Feynman–Kac formula, one can represent solutions to the Schrödinger equation in terms of the Wiener process.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] In physical cosmology, it also appears in models of eternal inflation.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] The Wiener process is prominent in the mathematical theory of finance as well, in particular the Black–Scholes option pricing model.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] W has independent increments: for every *t* > 0, the future increments ${\textstyle W_{t+u}-W_{t},\,u\geq 0,}$ are independent of the past values *Ws*, *s* < *t*.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] W has Gaussian increments: for all ${\textstyle u,t\geq 0}$ , ${\textstyle W_{t+u}-W_{t}\sim {\mathcal {N}}(0,u).}$ That is, a time step u results in an increment that is normally distributed with mean 0 and variance u.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] W has almost surely continuous paths: *Wt* is almost surely continuous in t.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] That the process has independent increments means that if 0 ≤ *s*1 < *t*1 ≤ *s*2 < *t*2 then *W**t*1 − *W**s*1 and *W**t*2 − *W**s*2 are independent random variables, and the similar condition holds for n increments.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] Condition 2 can equivalently be formulated: For every *t* > 0 and ${\textstyle u\geq 0}$ , the increment ${\textstyle W_{t+u}-W_{t}}$ is independent of the sigma-algebra ${\textstyle {\mathcal {F}}_{t}^{B}=\sigma (W_{s}:0\leq s\leq t).}$ .
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] An alternative characterisation of the Wiener process is the so-called *Lévy characterisation* that says that the Wiener process is an almost surely continuous martingale with *W*0 = 0 and quadratic variation [*W**t*, *W**t*] = *t* (which means that *W**t*2 − *t* is also a martingale).
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] A third characterisation is that the Wiener process has a spectral representation as a sine series whose coefficients are independent *N*(0, 1) random variables.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] This representation can be obtained using the Karhunen–Loève theorem.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] Another characterisation of a Wiener process is the definite integral (from time zero to time t) of a zero mean, unit variance, delta correlated ("white") Gaussian process.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] The Wiener process can be constructed as the scaling limit of a random walk, or other discrete-time stochastic processes with stationary independent increments.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] Unlike the random walk, it is scale invariant, meaning that $\alpha ^{-1}W_{\alpha ^{2}t}$ is a Wiener process for any nonzero constant α.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] The **Wiener measure** is the probability law on the space of continuous functions *g*, with *g*(0) = 0, induced by the Wiener process.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] An integral based on Wiener measure may be called a **Wiener integral**.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] Let ${\textstyle \xi _{1},\xi _{2},\ldots }$ be i.i.d. random variables with mean 0 and variance 1.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] For each n, define a continuous time stochastic process $W_{n}(t)={\frac {1}{\sqrt {n}}}\sum \limits _{1\leq k\leq \lfloor nt\rfloor }\xi _{k},\qquad t\in [0,1].$ This is a random step function.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] Increments of *Wn* are independent because the ${\textstyle \xi _{k}}$ are independent.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] For large n, ${\textstyle W_{n}(t)-W_{n}(s)}$ is close to ${\textstyle N(0,t-s)}$ by the central limit theorem.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] Donsker's theorem asserts that as ${\textstyle n\to \infty }$ , *Wn* approaches a Wiener process, which mathematically explains the ubiquity of Brownian motion in natural phenomena.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] These results follow immediately from the definition that increments have a normal distribution, centered at zero.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] These results follow from the definition that non-overlapping increments are independent, of which only the property that they are uncorrelated is used.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] A corollary useful for simulation is that we can write, for *t*1 < *t*2: $W_{t_{2}}=W_{t_{1}}+{\sqrt {t_{2}-t_{1}}}\cdot Z$ where Z is an independent standard normal variable.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] Wiener (1923) also gave a representation of a Brownian path in terms of a random Fourier series.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] The scaled process ${\sqrt {c}}\,W\left({\frac {t}{c}}\right)$ is a Brownian motion on ${\textstyle [0,c]}$ (cf.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] the probability density function of a Half-normal distribution.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] If at time t the Wiener process has a known value ${\textstyle W_{t}}$ , it is possible to calculate the conditional probability distribution of the maximum in interval ${\textstyle [0,t]}$ (cf.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] Probability distribution of extreme points of a Wiener stochastic process).
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] For every *c* > 0 the process ${\textstyle V_{t}=(1/{\sqrt {c}})W_{ct}}$ is another Wiener process.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] The process ${\textstyle V_{t}=tW_{1/t}}$ is another Wiener process.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] Consider a Wiener process ${\textstyle W(t)}$ , ${\textstyle t\in \mathbb {R} }$ , conditioned so that ${\textstyle \lim _{t\to \pm \infty }tW(t)=0}$ (which holds almost surely) and as usual ${\textstyle W(0)=0}$ .
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] Let ${\textstyle W(t)}$ be a two-dimensional Wiener process, regarded as a complex-valued process with ${\textstyle W(0)=0\in \mathbb {C} }$ .
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] About functions *p*(*xa*, *t*) more general than polynomials, see local martingales.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] The set of all functions w with these properties is of full Wiener measure.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] The dimension doubling theorems say that the Hausdorff dimension of a set under a Brownian motion doubles almost surely.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] The image of the Lebesgue measure on [0, *t*] under the map w (the pushforward measure) has a density *L**t*.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] Thus, $\int _{0}^{t}f(w(s))\,\mathrm {d} s=\int _{-\infty }^{+\infty }f(x)L_{t}(x)\,\mathrm {d} x$ for a wide class of functions f (namely: all continuous functions; all locally integrable functions; all non-negative measurable functions).
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] The density *Lt* is (more exactly, can and will be chosen to be) continuous.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] The number *Lt*(*x*) is called the local time at x of w on [0, *t*].
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] It is strictly positive for all x of the interval (*a*, *b*) where *a* and *b* are the least and the greatest value of w on [0, *t*], respectively.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] (For x outside this interval the local time evidently vanishes.) Treated as a function of two variables x and t, the local time is still continuous.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] Treated as a function of t (while x is fixed), the local time is a singular function corresponding to a nonatomic measure on the set of zeros of w.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] These continuity properties are fairly non-trivial.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] Consider that the local time can also be defined (as the density of the pushforward measure) for a smooth function.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] Then, however, the density is discontinuous, unless the given function is monotone.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] In other words, there is a conflict between good behavior of a function and good behavior of its local time.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] In this sense, the continuity of the local time of the Wiener process is another manifestation of non-smoothness of the trajectory.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] In many cases, it is impossible to encode the Wiener process without sampling it first.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] In particular, ${\textstyle T_{s}/6}$ is the mean squared error associated only with the sampling operation (without encoding).
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] The stochastic process defined by $X_{t}=\mu t+\sigma W_{t}$ is called a **Wiener process with drift μ** and infinitesimal variance σ2.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] These processes exhaust continuous Lévy processes, which means that they are the only continuous Lévy processes, as a consequence of the Lévy–Khintchine representation.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] Two random processes on the time interval [0, 1] appear, roughly speaking, when conditioning the Wiener process to vanish on both ends of [0,1].
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] With no further conditioning, the process takes both positive and negative values on [0, 1] and is called Brownian bridge.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] Conditioned also to stay positive on (0, 1), the process is called Brownian excursion.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] In both cases a rigorous treatment involves a limiting procedure, since the formula *P*(*A*|*B*) = *P*(*A* ∩ *B*)/*P*(*B*) does not apply when *P*(*B*) = 0.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] It is a stochastic process which is used to model processes that can never take on negative values, such as the value of stocks.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] The stochastic process $X_{t}=e^{-t}W_{e^{2t}}$ is distributed like the Ornstein–Uhlenbeck process with parameters ${\textstyle \theta =1}$ , ${\textstyle \mu =0}$ , and ${\textstyle \sigma ^{2}=2}$ .
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] The time of hitting a single point *x* > 0 by the Wiener process is a random variable with the Lévy distribution.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] The family of these random variables (indexed by all positive numbers x) is a left-continuous modification of a Lévy process.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] The right-continuous modification of this process is given by times of first exit from closed intervals [0, *x*].
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] The local time *L* = (*Lxt*)*x* ∈ **R**, *t* ≥ 0 of a Brownian motion describes the time that the process spends at the point x.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] The behaviour of the local time is characterised by Ray–Knight theorems.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] Then the process *Xt* is a continuous martingale.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] Its martingale property follows immediately from the definitions, but its continuity is a very special fact – a special case of a general theorem stating that all Brownian martingales are continuous.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] A Brownian martingale is, by definition, a martingale adapted to the Brownian filtration; and the Brownian filtration is, by definition, the filtration generated by the Wiener process.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] The time-integral of the Wiener process $W^{(-1)}(t):=\int _{0}^{t}W(s)\,ds$ is called **integrated Brownian motion** or **integrated Wiener process**.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] It arises in many applications and can be shown to have the distribution *N*(0, *t*3/3), calculated using the fact that the covariance of the Wiener process is ${\textstyle t\wedge s=\min(t,s)}$ .
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] All these results can be seen as direct consequences of Itô isometry.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] The *n*-times-integrated Wiener process is a zero-mean normal variable with variance ${\textstyle {\frac {t}{2n+1}}\left({\frac {t^{n}}{n!}}\right)^{2}}$ .
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] This is given by the Cauchy formula for repeated integration.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] Every continuous martingale (starting at the origin) is a time changed Wiener process.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] In general, if M is a continuous martingale then ${\textstyle M_{t}-M_{0}=V_{A(t)}}$ where *A*(*t*) is the quadratic variation of M on [0, *t*], and V is a Wiener process.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] Especially, a nonnegative continuous martingale has a finite limit (as *t* → ∞) almost surely.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] All stated (in this subsection) for martingales holds also for local martingales.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] A wide class of continuous semimartingales (especially, of diffusion processes) is related to the Wiener process via a combination of time change and change of measure.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] Using this fact, the qualitative properties stated above for the Wiener process can be generalized to a wide class of continuous semimartingales.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] The complex-valued Wiener process may be defined as a complex-valued random process of the form ${\textstyle Z_{t}=X_{t}+iY_{t}}$ where ${\textstyle X_{t}}$ and ${\textstyle Y_{t}}$ are independent Wiener processes (real-valued).
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] In other words, it is the 2-dimensional Wiener process, where we identify ${\textstyle \mathbb {R} ^{2}}$ with ${\textstyle \mathbb {C} }$ .
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] Brownian scaling, time reversal, time inversion: the same as in the real-valued case.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] Rotation invariance: for every complex number ${\textstyle c}$ such that ${\textstyle |c|=1}$ the process ${\textstyle c\cdot Z_{t}}$ is another complex-valued Wiener process.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] If ${\textstyle f}$ is an entire function then the process ${\textstyle f(Z_{t})-f(0)}$ is a time-changed complex-valued Wiener process.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] In contrast to the real-valued case, a complex-valued martingale is generally not a time-changed complex-valued Wiener process.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] For example, the martingale ${\textstyle 2X_{t}+iY_{t}}$ is not (here ${\textstyle X_{t}}$ and ${\textstyle Y_{t}}$ are independent Wiener processes, as before).
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] The Brownian sheet is a multiparamateric generalization.
[src:stochastic-calculus/wiener-process] The definition varies from authors, some define the Brownian sheet to have specifically a two-dimensional time parameter ${\textstyle t}$ while others define it for general dimensions.
